comments:
If you have a breakpoint with a condition that throws an NPE, you get an error
message that is not helpful in tracking down the problem.

To reproduce:

Use the following simple class:
---
package helloworld;

public class HelloWorld
{
	private String foo;

	public static void main(String[] args)
	{
		HelloWorld myThing = null;
		myThing = new HelloWorld();  // BREAKPOINT HERE
		System.out.println("Hello World!");
		System.out.println("My foo:" + myThing.foo);
	}
}
---

Put a breakpoint on the line that assigns a value to myThing, and put this
condition in the breakpoint:
  myThing.foo == null

When you debug, you'll get an error that says:
  JDI thread evaluations (Error: Exception processing async thread queue

Nothing about the error other than JDI indicates that the problem is coming from
a breakpoint, or which breakpoint.

In my case, this situation arose when a team member's check-in pushed my
breakpoint to a different method, where the condition would throw an NPE.
